Use [`IAuthorizationService`](https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/api/microsoft.aspnetcore.authorization.iauthorizationservice?view=aspnetcore-3.0) to perform [imperative authorization](https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/aspnet/core/security/authorization/resourcebased?view=aspnetcore-3.0#use-imperative-authorization). It&#39;s a little more involved inside of a `TagHelper `class, which doesn&#39;t have direct access to `HttpContext` and its `User` property. 

Here&#39;s an approach that uses the [`[ViewContext]`](https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/api/microsoft.aspnetcore.mvc.viewfeatures.viewcontextattribute?view=aspnetcore-3.0) attribute as a means to get hold of `HttpContext` and `User`, and uses dependency injection to get hold of the `IAuthorizationService`:

    public class PassportTagHelper : TagHelper
    {
        private readonly IAuthorizationService authorizationService;
    
        public PassportTagHelper(IAuthorizationService authorizationService)
        {
            this.authorizationService = authorizationService;
        }
    
        [ViewContext]
        public ViewContext ViewContext { get; set; }
    
        public override async Task ProcessAsync(TagHelperContext ctx, TagHelperOutput output)
        {
            var httpContext = ViewContext.HttpContext;
            var authorizationResult = await authorizationService
                .AuthorizeAsync(httpContext.User, &quot;UserHasRecentPassport&quot;);
    
            if (!authorizationResult.Succeeded)
                output.SuppressOutput();
            }
        }
    }

Things to note:

* `HttpContext` is access via the `ViewContext` property, which is set automatically when decorated with the `ViewContext` attribute.
* `Process` becomes `ProcessAsync`, so that it can `await` the call to `AuthorizeAsync`.
* The value returned from `AuthorizeAsync` is an [`AuthorizationResult`](https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/api/microsoft.aspnetcore.authorization.authorizationresult?view=aspnetcore-3.0), which indicates success via its `Succeeded` property and a reason for failure in its `Failure` property.

There are other options, such as injecting and using `IHttpContextAccessor` to get the `HttpContext` instance rather than using the `[ViewContext]` attribute. As a general rule, I try to avoid `IHttpContextAccessor` where possible, but that doesn&#39;t mean you should do the same.

